{"title_page": "Pok\u00e9mon World Championships", "text_new": "{{short description|Esports event}}\n{{Infobox sports league\n| title           = Pok\u00e9mon World Championships\n| current_season  = <!-- do not wikilink -->\n| current_season2 = <!-- do not wikilink -->\n| last_season     = \n| upcoming_season = <!-- do not wikilink; replace with current_season at the start of the new season -->\n| logo            = File:Pok\u00e9mon_World_Championships_logo.jpg\n| pixels          = \n| caption         = \n| formerly        = \n| replaced        = \n| game            = ''[[Pok\u00e9mon]]''\n| founded         = {{start date|2004}}\n| folded          = \n| owner           = [[The Pok\u00e9mon Company]]\n| ceo             = [[Tsunekazu Ishihara]]\n| director        = \n| president       =\n| commissioner    = [[Play! Pok\u00e9mon]]\n| fame            = <!--what the league is famous for...the \"claim to fame\"...avoid use if possible-->\n| motto           =\n| divisions       = <!-- as of 2020 -->\n* Junior (Born 2008 or later)\n* Senior (Born 2004-2007)\n* Masters (Born 2003 or earlier)\n| inaugural       = \n| teams           = \n| singles         = \n| countries       = \n| venue           = Rotating locations\n| headquarters    = [[Bellevue, Washington]], [[United States]]\n| continent       = <!-- or | continents = -->\n| champion        = \n| most_champs     = \n| qualification   = \n| tv              =\n| sponsor         =\n| related_comps   =\n| founder         = \n| levels          =\n| promotion       =\n| relegation      = \n| domestic_cup    =\n| website         = [https://www.pokemon.com/us/play-pokemon/ Play! Pok\u00e9mon Events]\n| footnotes       =\n}}\n\nThe '''Pok\u00e9mon World Championships''' is an invite-only [[esports]] event organized by [[The Pok\u00e9mon Company|The Pokemon Company]]. It is held annually in August and features games from the ''[[Pok\u00e9mon]]'' series such as the [[Pok\u00e9mon (video game series)|''Pok\u00e9mon'' video games]], ''[[Pok\u00e9mon Trading Card Game]]'', ''[[Pokk\u00e9n Tournament]]'' and ''[[Pok\u00e9mon Go]]''. Players earn invitations to the World Championships based on their performance in qualifiers and other tournaments held throughout the season and compete for scholarship money, prizes and the title of World Champion. With the exception of [[Japan]] and [[South Korea]], invitations to the World Championships are administered by the [[Play! Pok\u00e9mon]] program.\n\n==History==\nThe Pok\u00e9mon World Championships first began with the [[Pok\u00e9mon Trading Card Game]] (TCG) in 2004. In 2009, Play! Pok\u00e9mon began to organize competitive tournaments for the ''Pok\u00e9mon'' video game series alongside the TCG, which is collectively known as the Video Game Championships (VGC). Like the TCG Championships, players compete with other players in their own age divisions (i.e. Junior, Senior and Masters) in different Premier Tournaments, and the season culminates with the best players earning an invitation to play the Pok\u00e9mon World Championships in August. The tournaments in VGC are played with a different game each year. \n\nIn 2016, Play! Pok\u00e9mon announced that ''[[Pokk\u00e9n Tournament]]'' will have its own championship series and will be played at the Pok\u00e9mon World Championships.<ref>Official Pokk\u00e9n Tournament website, http://www.pokkentournament.com/en-us/championship-series/</ref>\n\nIn 2019, it was announced that the 2020 Pok\u00e9mon World Championships would take place at [[London]], [[United Kingdom]],<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\" /> the first time in which the World Championships would be held in a location outside of [[North America]]. This is likely due to the setting of [[Pok\u00e9mon Sword and Shield|''Pok\u00e9mon Sword and Shield'']], which takes place in a region inspired by the United Kingdom, and it is the set of games that would be played by the video game division of the World Championships.  \n\nOn March 31, 2020, [[Play! Pok\u00e9mon]] cancelled the 2020 Pok\u00e9mon World Championships and suspended its 2020 season due to health concerns over the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pokemon.com/us/pokemon-news/2020-pokemon-championship-series-canceled/|title=2020 Pok\u00e9mon Championship Series Canceled {{!}} Pokemon.com|website=www.pokemon.com|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dailyesports.gg/2020-pokemon-championship-series-suspended-due-to-coronavirus/|title=2020 Pok\u00e9mon Championship Series suspended due to coronavirus|date=2020-03-31|website=Daily Esports|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref> This came after earlier announcements in March which saw the cancellation of the 2020 European International Championships<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pokemon.com/us/pokemon-news/update-for-the-2020-pokemon-europe-international-championships/|title=Update for the 2020 Pok\u00e9mon Europe International Championships {{!}} Pokemon.com|website=www.pokemon.com|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.espn.com/esports/story/_/id/28852369/pokemon-cancels-europe-international-championship-coronavirus-cases-swell|title=Pok\u00e9mon championship canceled as coronavirus cases swell|date=2020-03-06|website=ESPN.com|language=en|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref> and part of its season between March and May 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dailyesports.gg/play-pokemon-cancels-more-sanctioned-events-due-to-coronavirus/|title=Play Pok\u00e9mon cancels more sanctioned events due to coronavirus|date=2020-03-17|website=Daily Esports|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/esports-arena-leagues-shift-online-events-coronavirus-pandemic-1285112|title=Esports Arena: Leagues Shift to Online Events Amid Coronavirus Pandemic|website=The Hollywood Reporter|language=en|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref> \n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n! Year\n!Location\n